en essays are a fitting tribute to her memory. Written by recognized North American scholars, the essays explore various aspects of Christology, inviting the reader to probe the meaning and significance of Jesus Christ for today. They address a broad range of issues, including the Christology of the Acts of Thomas, Hooker on divinization, and Christ figures in contemporary Canadian culture. Teachers of theology and religious studies, pastors, and informed general readers will find the essays stimulating and instructive. They present the readers with considered, mature, and current scholarship. These are the questions that engaged Joanne McWilliam throughout her life, and she was happy to know that the critical dialogue would continue in this volume as friends and colleagues wrestled with Christological questions. For her, “In Jesus we come to know the compassion, the power, the wisdom, the love, and the faithfulness of God”.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLogos (Christian theology). 0aReligion and ethics. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / Christology.2bisacsh1 aBeavis, Mary Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoyle, J. Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrysdale, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Bruyn, Theodore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFahey, Michael A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGood, Deirdre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Elizabeth A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeonard, Ellen M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLeonard, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul